## Migration: `BackgroundProcessor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Analysis

Your code has three Thread.Abort-related APIs that **throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+**:

| API Found | Location | Pattern |
|-----------|----------|---------|
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ProcessLoop()` | Control flow cleanup |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `ProcessLoop()` | Continue after abort |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — same logic that was in the
                // ThreadAbortException catch block
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for the thread to finish gracefully.
        // Join replaces the old Thread.Sleep(2000) + Abort pattern.
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        // If the thread is still alive after 2s, it means GetNextItem or
        // ProcessItem is stuck in a call that doesn't check the token.
        // There is NO equivalent to Thread.Abort in modern .NET.
        // See "Uncooperative code" pitfall below.
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

### What Changed and Why

| Old (.NET Framework) | New (.NET 8) | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationTokenSource` / `CancellationToken` | Unified cancellation model; token can also interrupt blocking calls |
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+ |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | `OperationCanceledException` is the cooperative equivalent; the `when` guard avoids catching unrelated OCEs |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | No longer needed — `OperationCanceledException` does not auto-rethrow like `ThreadAbortException` did |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread.Join(2000)` | Actually waits for the thread instead of sleeping blindly |
| *(nothing)* | `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable` — leaking it leaks timers and callbacks |

### Critical Pitfalls

**1. `GetNextItem()` must accept and respect the token.**
The comment says it "may block." If it blocks on I/O or a queue, the token alone won't interrupt it. You must update the implementation:

```csharp
// If it uses a BlockingCollection<T>:
var item = _queue.Take(token); // wakes up on cancellation

// If it uses Thread.Sleep or WaitHandle:
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(pollInterval); // replaces Thread.Sleep

// If it does synchronous socket/DB I/O:
// Switch to async overloads that accept CancellationToken,
// or use token.Register(() => socket.Close()) to interrupt the call.
```

**2. There is no forced kill in modern .NET.**
If `GetNextItem` calls third-party code that ignores the token, the thread will hang. The only escape hatch is moving that work to a **child process** and calling `Process.Kill()`.

**3. Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException` broadly.**
The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures you only catch cancellations *you* initiated, not unrelated ones from inner async calls.

**4. Token must flow through the entire call chain.**
Every method in the chain (`GetNextItem`, `ProcessItem`, any sub-calls) must accept and forward the `CancellationToken`, or cancellation stalls at the first method that doesn't check it.
